RECOMMENDATIONS
A new generation of low-earth orbiting and geostationary satellites
have the potential to estimate ozone levels near the earth’s surface.
A CONSTELLATION OF GEOSTATIONARY SATELLITES – THE NEXT
GENERATION IN AIR QUALITY MONITORING – AUGMENTED BY LOW
EARTH-ORBITING SATELLITES WOULD REVOLUTIONIZE GLOBAL AND
REGIONAL MONITORING.
THE FULL SUITE OF SATELLITE OBSERVATIONS NEED TO BE USED TO
CONSTRAIN BOTH OZONE PRECURSOR EMISSIONS AND OZONE
CONCENTRATIONS.
AIR QUALITY MONITORING SHOULD BE ANCHORED ON AN
OPERATIONAL AIR QUALITY ANALYSIS SYSTEM THAT
ASSIMILATES SATELLITE, AIRCRAFT, AND IN-SITU
OBSERVATIONS WITH GLOBAL AND REGIONAL CHEMICAL
TRANSPORT MODELS.
SURFACE OZONE OBSERVATION NETWORKS NEED TO BE
DEVELOPED AND EXPANDED. SURFACE OZONE OBSERVATION
NETWORKS NEED TO BE DEVELOPED AND EXPANDED. OZONE
NETWORKS CAN BE OPTIMALLY CONSTRUCTED FOR A MODEST
INVESTMENT.
USE OF MULTISPECTRAL TECHNIQUES AND INSTRUMENTATION
SHOULD BE USED TO MEASURE BOUNDARY LAYER OZONE AND
CARBON MONOXIDE.
THE ROLE OF THIS SYSTEM FOR THE MONITORING OF AIR
QUALITY-CLIMATE CO-BENEFITS SHOULD BE INVESTIGATED.
